quickjs-js/--background--                            quickjs-js/--background--

    NAME
	quickjs.library JavaScript API -- features available to
	    scripts running under qjs / quickjs.library

    SCOPE
	This document describes the JavaScript API surface, i.e.
	what is callable from `.js` files run by qjs (or any
	program that opens quickjs.library and exposes the std/os
	modules to its scripts).

	For the C-side library API (the QJS_* LVO functions), see
	the companion document quickjs.doc.

    LANGUAGE LEVEL
	Full ES2020+, including:

	    classes, modules, async/await, generators
	    Promise, Map/Set, WeakMap/WeakSet, WeakRef
	    BigInt, Symbol, TypedArrays, DataView, ArrayBuffer
	    Proxy, Reflect, optional chaining, nullish coalescing
	    Iterator helpers, Promise.withResolvers
	    JSON modules, import attributes, RegExp v flag

	The engine is QuickJS-ng 0.12.1 -- see the upstream
	docs for the full ECMAScript surface.

    AMIGA EXTENSIONS
	Beyond standard ECMAScript, the Amiga port adds:

	    * print() and console.log() globals
	    * Symbol.for('qjs.inspect') for custom display
	    * fetch() with Response and Headers (web-style HTTP)
	    * std and os modules with Amiga-aware file/process/
	      timer APIs
	    * S:QJS-Startup.js auto-loaded on REPL/script start
	    * S:QJS-Config.txt for default CLI flags

    SEE ALSO
	--repl--, --startup--, fetch, std.urlGet,
	Symbol.qjs.inspect


quickjs-js/--repl--                                          quickjs-js/--repl--

    NAME
	--repl-- -- Interactive JavaScript shell

    USAGE
	Run `qjs` with no script argument to enter the REPL:

	    1> qjs
	    QuickJS-ng - Type ".help" for help
	    qjs > 1 + 1
	    2
	    qjs > await fetch('https://example.com')
	    Response { ... }
	    qjs > .quit

    KEYBOARD
	Most readline-style key bindings work:
	    Backspace      -- delete char left
	    Left/Right     -- move cursor
	    Up/Down        -- history
	    Home/End       -- start/end of line
	    Tab            -- completion
	    Ctrl-C         -- abort current line / exit
	    Ctrl-D         -- EOF (exit)

    DOT COMMANDS
	    .help          -- list commands
	    .quit          -- exit
	    .clear         -- clear screen
	    .load FILE     -- evaluate a file
	    .save FILE     -- save history to file

    DISPLAY
	The result of each expression is printed using
	JS_PrintValue, which honours Symbol.for('qjs.inspect')
	on objects.

    SEE ALSO
	Symbol.qjs.inspect, --startup--


quickjs-js/--startup--                                    quickjs-js/--startup--

    NAME
	--startup-- -- S:QJS-Startup.js and S:QJS-Config.txt

    S:QJS-CONFIG.TXT
	A plain-text file with one CLI option per line.  Read
	BEFORE the user's command-line arguments are parsed.
	Lines starting with # are comments; blank lines are
	ignored.

	Example:

	    # default config for qjs
	    --std
	    --color
	    -m

	The user's actual command-line arguments override entries
	from this file.

    S:QJS-STARTUP.JS
	If this file exists, it is evaluated AFTER std/os are
	registered but BEFORE any user code (REPL or script).
	Errors in the startup file are non-fatal and printed to
	stderr.

	Use cases:
	    * register custom REPL helpers
	    * import frequently-used modules
	    * apply Symbol.for('qjs.inspect') to your favourite
	      classes
	    * set up app-wide globals

	Example:

	    import * as std from 'qjs:std';
	    globalThis.cat = (path) => {
		const f = std.open(path, 'r');
		const buf = f.readAsString();
		f.close();
		return buf;
	    };

    SEE ALSO
	--repl--


quickjs-js/print                                                  quickjs-js/print

    NAME
	print -- Write values to stdout, then a newline.

    SYNOPSIS
	print(...args)

    FUNCTION
	Writes each argument to stdout, separated by spaces, then
	a newline.  Strings are written verbatim; non-string
	values go through JS_PrintValue (which honours
	Symbol.for('qjs.inspect')).

    EXAMPLE
	print("hello", { x: 1 });
	// hello { x: 1 }

    SEE ALSO
	console.log, Symbol.qjs.inspect, std.printf


quickjs-js/console.log                                      quickjs-js/console.log

    NAME
	console.log -- Alias for print(), with stdout flush.

    SYNOPSIS
	console.log(...args)

    FUNCTION
	Same as print() but additionally calls fflush(stdout)
	before returning.  Use this when you need the output
	visible before the next blocking call (otherwise stdio
	may buffer the line).

    SEE ALSO
	print


quickjs-js/Symbol.qjs.inspect                          quickjs-js/Symbol.qjs.inspect

    NAME
	Symbol.for('qjs.inspect') -- Custom display in print()
	    and the REPL.

    USAGE
	Define a method on your object (or its prototype) keyed
	by Symbol.for('qjs.inspect'):

	    class Money {
		constructor(amount, ccy) {
		    this.amount = amount;
		    this.ccy = ccy;
		}
		[Symbol.for('qjs.inspect')]() {
		    return `${this.ccy}${this.amount.toFixed(2)}`;
		}
	    }
	    print(new Money(42.5, '$'));   // $42.50

    BEHAVIOUR
	When JS_PrintValue encounters an object during print() or
	REPL display, it looks up Symbol.for('qjs.inspect') on
	the object via the prototype chain.  If found and
	callable, it is invoked with no arguments; if it returns
	a string, that string is emitted instead of the default
	{ ... } rendering.

	If the method throws or returns a non-string, the default
	rendering is used.

    NOTES
	Inspired by Node.js's util.inspect.custom symbol.
	Amiga-port-only feature; not part of standard ECMAScript.

    SEE ALSO
	print, --repl--


quickjs-js/fetch                                                  quickjs-js/fetch

    NAME
	fetch -- Async HTTP/HTTPS request, returning Promise<Response>.

    SYNOPSIS
	const response = await fetch(url, options?);

    PARAMETERS
	url     - String "http://..." or "https://...".
	options - Optional object:
		    method    - "GET" (default), "POST", "PUT",
				"DELETE", etc.
		    headers   - String of "Name: Value\r\n" lines
				to append to the request (object
				form not yet supported -- v0.65).
		    body      - String body for POST/PUT.

    RETURN
	Promise<Response> -- resolves on success, rejects with
	TypeError on network errors (DNS failure, connection
	refused, TLS handshake failure, ...).

    REQUIREMENTS
	* TCP/IP stack running (Roadshow, AmiTCP, Miami, ...).
	* For HTTPS: AmiSSL installed.

    EXAMPLE
	// GET
	const r = await fetch('https://example.com');
	console.log(r.status);             // 200
	console.log(await r.text());

	// JSON GET
	const data =
	    await (await fetch('https://httpbin.org/json')).json();

	// POST
	const r = await fetch('https://httpbin.org/post', {
	    method: 'POST',
	    body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Amiga' }),
	});

    HOW IT WORKS
	Each fetch() spawns a dedicated worker process via
	AmigaOS CreateNewProc().  The worker performs the
	blocking HTTP/HTTPS work (DNS, connect, TLS handshake,
	send, recv) while the main task remains responsive --
	the REPL keeps accepting input, timers keep firing.

	When the worker finishes, it posts a message to a reply
	port.  The main task polls the port every 20ms via
	setTimeout; the Promise resolves on receipt.

    LIMITATIONS (v0.65)
	* One concurrent fetch -- a second call while one is in
	  flight rejects with "fetch already in progress".
	* No automatic 3xx redirect following.
	* Body fully buffered (no streaming).
	* HTTP/1.0 only (no chunked encoding, no keep-alive).
	* `headers` option must be a raw string, not an object.

    SEE ALSO
	Response, Headers, std.urlGet


quickjs-js/Response                                          quickjs-js/Response

    NAME
	Response -- HTTP response object, returned by fetch().

    PROPERTIES
	status      -- HTTP status code (number, e.g. 200, 404)
	ok          -- boolean: true if status is 200-299
	statusText  -- short reason phrase (best-effort,
		       inferred from status code)
	url         -- final URL string
	headers     -- Headers object

    METHODS
	text()        -> Promise<string>
	json()        -> Promise<any>
	arrayBuffer() -> Promise<ArrayBuffer>

    EXAMPLE
	const r = await fetch('https://example.com');
	if (r.ok) {
	    const html = await r.text();
	    console.log(html.length);
	}

    NOTES
	The body is fully buffered when the Response is created.
	The text/json/arrayBuffer methods all operate on the same
	underlying buffer; calling them does not consume it (you
	can call multiple times).

    SEE ALSO
	fetch, Headers


quickjs-js/Response.status                              quickjs-js/Response.status

    NAME
	Response.status -- HTTP status code.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.status   // number

    EXAMPLE
	(await fetch('https://example.com')).status   // 200
	(await fetch('http://httpbin.org/status/404')).status   // 404

    SEE ALSO
	Response.ok, Response.statusText


quickjs-js/Response.ok                                          quickjs-js/Response.ok

    NAME
	Response.ok -- True if status is 200-299.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.ok   // boolean

    EXAMPLE
	if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${r.status}`);

    SEE ALSO
	Response.status


quickjs-js/Response.statusText                           Response.statusText

    NAME
	Response.statusText -- Reason phrase associated with the
	    status code.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.statusText   // string

    NOTES
	The Amiga port reconstructs this from the status code
	(e.g. 200 -> "OK", 404 -> "Not Found") rather than from
	the wire data, since most servers omit the reason phrase
	in HTTP/1.1 anyway.

    SEE ALSO
	Response.status


quickjs-js/Response.url                                        quickjs-js/Response.url

    NAME
	Response.url -- The URL that was fetched.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.url   // string

    NOTES
	Always equal to the URL passed to fetch().  In future
	versions, after redirect handling is added, this will be
	the final URL.


quickjs-js/Response.headers                              quickjs-js/Response.headers

    NAME
	Response.headers -- Response headers as a Headers object.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.headers   // Headers

    EXAMPLE
	const r = await fetch('https://example.com');
	console.log(r.headers.get('Content-Type'));

    SEE ALSO
	Headers


quickjs-js/Response.text                                    quickjs-js/Response.text

    NAME
	Response.text() -- Body as a string.

    SYNOPSIS
	const s = await r.text();

    RETURN
	Promise<string> -- the response body decoded as UTF-8.

    EXAMPLE
	console.log(await (await fetch(url)).text());

    SEE ALSO
	Response.json, Response.arrayBuffer


quickjs-js/Response.json                                    quickjs-js/Response.json

    NAME
	Response.json() -- Body parsed as JSON.

    SYNOPSIS
	const obj = await r.json();

    RETURN
	Promise<any> -- the parsed JSON value.

    THROWS
	The promise rejects with SyntaxError if the body is not
	valid JSON.

    EXAMPLE
	const data = await (await fetch('/api/info')).json();

    SEE ALSO
	Response.text


quickjs-js/Response.arrayBuffer                       quickjs-js/Response.arrayBuffer

    NAME
	Response.arrayBuffer() -- Body as a binary buffer.

    SYNOPSIS
	const buf = await r.arrayBuffer();

    RETURN
	Promise<ArrayBuffer> -- the raw bytes.

    EXAMPLE
	const buf = await (await fetch(imageUrl)).arrayBuffer();
	const bytes = new Uint8Array(buf);
	std.writeFile('RAM:image.png', bytes);

    SEE ALSO
	Response.text


quickjs-js/Headers                                              quickjs-js/Headers

    NAME
	Headers -- Read-only HTTP header bag (response headers).

    METHODS
	get(name)        -> string | null
	has(name)        -> boolean
	forEach(cb)      -> calls cb(value, name) per header

    NOTES
	Created by fetch() and accessed via Response.headers.
	Cannot be constructed directly in v0.65 (no Headers()
	constructor exposed yet).  Header lookups are
	case-insensitive.

    SEE ALSO
	Headers.get, Headers.has, Headers.forEach, Response


quickjs-js/Headers.get                                      quickjs-js/Headers.get

    NAME
	Headers.get(name) -- Look up a header value.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.headers.get(name)   // string | null

    PARAMETERS
	name - Header name (case-insensitive).

    RETURN
	The header value as a string, or null if absent.

    EXAMPLE
	const ct = r.headers.get('Content-Type');   // "text/html"
	r.headers.get('content-type')               // same


quickjs-js/Headers.has                                      quickjs-js/Headers.has

    NAME
	Headers.has(name) -- Test for header presence.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.headers.has(name)   // boolean

    EXAMPLE
	if (r.headers.has('Set-Cookie')) {
	    /* ... */
	}


quickjs-js/Headers.forEach                              quickjs-js/Headers.forEach

    NAME
	Headers.forEach(cb) -- Iterate over headers.

    SYNOPSIS
	r.headers.forEach((value, name) => { ... })

    EXAMPLE
	r.headers.forEach((v, n) => print(`${n}: ${v}`));

    NOTES
	Argument order matches the Web Fetch spec: value first,
	name second.


quickjs-js/std.in                                                quickjs-js/std.in
quickjs-js/std.out                                              quickjs-js/std.out

    NAME
	std.in / std.out / std.err -- Standard FILE objects.

    USAGE
	import * as std from 'qjs:std';
	std.out.puts("hello\n");
	const line = std.in.getline();

    METHODS (on FILE)
	puts(s)         -- write a string
	printf(fmt,...) -- formatted write
	read(buf, off, n) -> bytes read
	write(buf, off, n) -> bytes written
	getline()       -> string (one line, sans newline) or null
	flush()         -- flush buffer
	close()         -- close handle

    SEE ALSO
	std.open


quickjs-js/std.exit                                            quickjs-js/std.exit

    NAME
	std.exit(code) -- Exit the program.

    SYNOPSIS
	std.exit(code)

    PARAMETERS
	code - Exit status (0 for success).

    NOTES
	On AmigaOS, returns to the calling shell with the given
	RC.  Throws inside the engine to unwind cleanly.


quickjs-js/std.gc                                                quickjs-js/std.gc

    NAME
	std.gc() -- Force a GC cycle.

    SEE ALSO
	-- (C-side: QJS_RunGC)


quickjs-js/std.getenv                                        quickjs-js/std.getenv

    NAME
	std.getenv(name) -- Read an environment variable.

    SYNOPSIS
	std.getenv(name)   // string | undefined

    NOTES
	On AmigaOS, reads dos.library variables (GetVar).  Note
	that NO_COLOR is forced to "1" by default to keep ANSI
	color codes out of the REPL on bare consoles; override
	with `setenv NO_COLOR 0` in the shell.

    SEE ALSO
	os.getvar


quickjs-js/std.printf                                        quickjs-js/std.printf

    NAME
	std.printf(fmt, ...args) -- Formatted write to stdout.

    SYNOPSIS
	std.printf("%d items\n", n);

    NOTES
	Subset of C printf supported (%d, %u, %x, %s, %c, %p,
	%f, %e, %g, %%).  Float formatting goes through the
	library's custom dtoa.


quickjs-js/std.urlGet                                        quickjs-js/std.urlGet

    NAME
	std.urlGet(url, options?) -- Synchronous HTTP/HTTPS GET.

    SYNOPSIS
	const body = std.urlGet(url, { full: true, binary: false })

    PARAMETERS
	url     - "http://..." or "https://..."
	options -
	    full   - if true, return { response, responseHeaders, status }
	    binary - if true, return ArrayBuffer; else string

    RETURN
	String, ArrayBuffer, or { response, responseHeaders,
	status } object.  Returns null on non-2xx unless
	`full: true`.

    NOTES
	BLOCKS the entire library until complete.  Use fetch()
	for async behaviour that keeps the REPL/event loop
	responsive.

    SEE ALSO
	fetch


quickjs-js/std.open                                            quickjs-js/std.open

    NAME
	std.open(path, mode) -- Open a file.

    SYNOPSIS
	const f = std.open("RAM:foo.txt", "w");

    PARAMETERS
	path - File path (Amiga or POSIX-style).
	mode - "r", "w", "a", "rb", "wb", "ab", with optional "+".

    RETURN
	FILE object with puts/printf/read/write/getline/flush/close.

    SEE ALSO
	std.in, std.loadFile, std.writeFile


quickjs-js/std.loadFile                                    quickjs-js/std.loadFile

    NAME
	std.loadFile(path) -- Read entire file as string.

    SYNOPSIS
	const s = std.loadFile("S:Startup-Sequence");


quickjs-js/std.writeFile                                  quickjs-js/std.writeFile

    NAME
	std.writeFile(path, data) -- Write data to a file.

    SYNOPSIS
	std.writeFile("RAM:out.txt", "hello\n");

    PARAMETERS
	data - String or Uint8Array/ArrayBuffer.


quickjs-js/os.exec                                              quickjs-js/os.exec

    NAME
	os.exec(args, options?) -- Run a shell command.

    SYNOPSIS
	const rc = os.exec(["dir", "RAM:"]);

    NOTES
	On AmigaOS, uses dos.library SystemTagList() to launch
	the command synchronously and return its exit code.

    SEE ALSO
	os.pipe


quickjs-js/os.pipe                                              quickjs-js/os.pipe

    NAME
	os.pipe() -- Create a pipe.

    NOTES
	Uses the AmigaOS PIPE: device.  Returns [readFd, writeFd].
	Requires PIPE: handler installed (standard since OS 3.0).


quickjs-js/os.kill                                              quickjs-js/os.kill

    NAME
	os.kill(pid, sig) -- Send a signal to a task.

    NOTES
	Uses Signal() with AmigaOS break flags.  Limited use on
	classic AmigaOS without process IDs in the POSIX sense.


quickjs-js/os.now                                                quickjs-js/os.now

    NAME
	os.now() -- Microseconds since the Unix epoch.

    NOTES
	Resolution is 20ms (50Hz tick).  Returns 0 on systems
	whose RTC has not been set.

    SEE ALSO
	os.setTimeout


quickjs-js/os.sleep                                            quickjs-js/os.sleep

    NAME
	os.sleep(ms) -- Block for `ms` milliseconds.

    NOTES
	Resolution 20ms.  Uses dos.library Delay().


quickjs-js/os.setTimeout                                  quickjs-js/os.setTimeout

    NAME
	os.setTimeout(fn, ms) -- Schedule a function.

    NOTES
	Resolution 20ms.  Returns a timer id usable with
	os.clearTimeout().


quickjs-js/os.setReadHandler                            os.setReadHandler

    NAME
	os.setReadHandler(fd, fn) -- Register an FD callback.

    NOTES
	On AmigaOS, only fd 0 (stdin) is meaningful.  Network
	sockets do NOT integrate (use fetch() instead).


quickjs-js/os.platform                                      quickjs-js/os.platform

    NAME
	os.platform -- String identifying the host OS.

    VALUE
	"amigaos"


quickjs-js/os.open                                              quickjs-js/os.open

    NAME
	os.open(path, flags, mode?) -- POSIX-style open.

    SEE ALSO
